@jan 13

Sophocles
  Oedipus Rex goes to Thebes but can't get in cos theres this massive Sphinx guarding it, unless he answers a particular riddle. If you don't answer correctly he gets eaten. 

  What would be evident to Wells' readers is how this riddle is used by Thomas Carlyse in 'Past and Present'. 
  carlyse introduces another sphinx but for himt he riddle is what to do with the working class. It's appropriate in a way that Wells would use this symbol. Carlyse has a slightly diff take on it; both talk about how put down the working class is, Carlyse talks about the responsiblity of the captains of industry to take care of the working class. 

  Other context for decadence is decadent art that emphasizes self indulgence, aesthetics, content, effort.

  Establishes narrative logic with other assumptions and interpretations, and everytime he gives us an interpretation he says but how wrong I was! dun dun dun duuuun. 

  He meets the Eloi; they are unconcerned, flower children. 

  Hypothesis by the Time Traveler
    1. A kind of Eden; he's sitting at the top of a hill looking out at this kind of vista, "it was as sweet and fair view as I have ever seen".
      A kind of statis-complacency, how they've lost necessity. 
      
    2. Two species theory. He realises after seeing the Morlocks and understands them that he has not this eden with a race of Eloi achieving some kind of stasis but rather two species where the morlocks constitute the underclass who have literally been driven underground.
      The Eloi are dominant.

    3. Morlock's ascendent. 
      Oops, I think I know what the Morlocks are eating. The Eloi are the ones who have become the victims and is split between disgust and a recognition that the Eloi kind of got what they deserved.

@jan 28

klaatu is a sympathetic figure, and the viewer is encouraged to identify with him instead of the media misrepresenting him and the army chasing him.

We in the audience know that he's a regular guy and there's this ironic dist that makes us suspicious of the media. In case thats not enough he's also represented as a kind of christ figure. Her question to us now is, in what respect what did we notice about his story that makes him into a christ like figure.

in day earth stood still,

klaatu - justice, US
earth - USSR/all rogue nations
Fed of Planets - UN/NATO
gort - atomic bomb

Different text.
Written at almost the same time, 1953, it has a v. different preoccupation. It picks up some of the themes of both the time machine and the day the earth stood still. Fahrenheit 451.

Similar themes w/time machine
- consumed by entertainment/leisure
  loss of knowledge, dumbing down, in particular of history
power relations
  class
  gov't/fire fighters
    People are being actively controlled and oppressed.
post-literate societies
  - in TM books literally crumbled to dust over 800k years
  - in F451 books are being burned, actively destroyed
language makes us human

whole story is about montag learning about literature.
In f451 the govt wants to keep people in the eternal present and hamstring any kind of social transformation. If you can't imagine anything other than what exists right now, there is no understanding on how to make things different and bradbury makes his claim that one way of understanding this is thru literature.


FF - active coercion
FF - active witness, part of society

TM - outsider, evolution/devolution
In f451 it's all about the protagonist and his journey from an enforcer to a kind of rebel.

What about the nature of the devolution?

psychologically vs physically devolved. In case of TM, traditionaly hard sci fi long periods of time, where as in f451 time frame much more compressed. Don't look any different physically.
active resistence vs passive acceptance.


both books have this female character who introduces the conflict and guide the plot.

@feb 2

mildred represents this deep disatisfaction that underlies people n this society. you dont attempt suicide unless you're at the point of despair, tho she doesn't remember clearly at some unconscious level that she's desperate.

something is very very wrong, something we don't see in the time machine. because theres this deep disatisfaction it suggest possibility for change. ofc we also see montg dev this sense first with his encounter with clarice,

she introduces this very inconvenient question, are you happy?
by pg 12 he felt his smile slide away, melt, fold over down on itself like a tallow skin, like the stuff of a fantastic candle blown out, darkness. he was not happy. 

beaty clearly has a couple of functions, clearly acts as his super ego, keeping him in line, but he also acts as a kind of explicator, to explain how tihs society came about, with these extended monologues with beaty. Another diff from the tm where we have a char who undergoes all these hypothesis trying to get it right, here we have someone who delivers the history to montag.

